  "prompt": "How can the Shia Kalma qualify for Shahdah as it distorts the fundamental word of Allah (SWT) by modifying the Tayyibah kalimat a\u1e6d-\u1e6daiyibah?",
  "response": "The term \"Shahada\" or testimony in Islam, particularly when considering the Islamic declaration of faith (the Kalima), refers specifically to the testifying that there is no god but Allah and that Muhammad is His messenger. The traditional formulation of the Shahada in Sunni Islam is:\n\n**\"Ashhadu an la ilaha illallah, wahdahu la sharika lahu, wa ashhadu anna Muhammadur rasulullah.\"**\n\nThis translates to: \"I bear witness that there is no deity but Allah, alone, without partner, and I bear witness that Muhammad is His messenger.\"\n\nIn Shia Islam, the Shahada includes an additional phrase, usually emphasizing the leadership of Ali ibn Abi Talib, the first Imam and cousin of the Prophet Muhammad. A common formulation among Shia Muslims is:\n\n**\"Ashhadu an la ilaha illallah, wahdahu la sharika lahu, wa ashhadu anna Muhammadur rasulullah, wa ashhadu anna Aliyyan waliullah.\"**\n\nThis translates to: \"I bear witness that there is no deity but Allah, alone, without partner, and I bear witness that Muhammad is His messenger, and I bear witness that Ali is the friend (or guardian) of Allah.\"\n\nThe debate about whether this modified declaration distorts the fundamental words of Allah often arises from differing theological interpretations within the Sunni and Shia communities. Shia Muslims argue that the additional testimony about Ali reflects his essential role in the leadership of the Muslim community and the rightful succession following the Prophet Muhammad. They do not see this as a distortion but rather as a crucial aspect of their faith that emphasizes the importance of the Ahl al-Bayt (the family of the Prophet).\n\nIn essence, this difference in formulations reflects a broader theological distinction rather than a violation or distortion of the core tenets of Islamic belief. Both groups maintain that their respective affirmations are rooted in the teachings of the Prophet and his family. The perspective on whether the addition is acceptable or indicative of distortion heavily depends on one's sectarian viewpoint within Islam.",
